    36	### Step 1 - Freeze The Implication Sheet To Be Tested
    37	
    38	This step is weaker than it looks because most of its content is already on
    39	disk.
    40	
    41	- Step 6 already froze the promoted gates without an exact implication between
    42	  them.
    43	- Step 7 already froze the downstream authority sheet and same-currency rule on
    44	  the canonical packet ledger.
    45	- Step 8 already recorded that the branch lacks one finite exact closure ledger
    46	  for `F_SS(1/12)`.
    47	
    48	So Step 1 is not really isolating a new research object. It is mostly restating
    49	the current dossier.
    50	
    51	The more serious problem is quantifier ambiguity. "Does `G_tmpl` imply finite
    52	closure" can mean at least four different things:
    53	
    54	- for the single frozen witness `F_SS(1/12)`,
    55	- for every packet on the canonical one-bridge ledger,
    56	- for every packet that passes the repaired thresholds,
    57	- or in the much weaker record-relative sense "can the current repository
    58	  derive closure from this gate."
    59	
    60	Those are not interchangeable. The chain never freezes which one it means, so
    61	the rest of the plan can drift between witness-local failure and theorem-level
    62	non-implication.
    63	
    64	Kill-condition problem:
    65	
    66	- The stated kill condition is far too weak. The branch should also stop if it
    67	  cannot freeze the quantifier domain and the exact meaning of "implies."
    68	- It should also stop if the implication sheet is already effectively answered
    69	  by existing Step-6 to Step-8 notes and only needs packaging.
    70	
    71	### Step 2 - State One Honest Exact-Closure Predicate On The Same Ledger
    72	
    73	This is the chain's real choke point, and the current record already says it is
    74	not solved.
    75	
    76	- The repository explicitly says it does not yet freeze one support-level exact
    77	  closure realization for `F_SS(1/12)`: no explicit wavevector family, no
    78	  fixed helicity assignment, no exact coefficient ledger, and no finite closure
    79	  convention that lists which forced companions must remain.
    80	- Because of that, Step 8 stopped at a raw classwise closure-burden ledger
    81	  rather than a finite exact subsystem.
    82	
    83	That means Step 2 is not a normal definition step. It is asking the branch to
    84	repair exactly the thing the record says is still unfrozen.
    85	
    86	The example predicate is also suspect. "Existence of one finite exact closed
    87	subsystem" sounds innocent, but in this context it can smuggle in a new support
    88	choice, a new truncation rule, or a new closure convention. If the branch gets
    89	to choose one existential witness after the fact, it has already relaxed the
    90	freeze discipline that Step 8 was defending.
    91	
    92	Kill-condition problem:
    93	
    94	- The kill condition should not just reject support-semantic changes and
    95	  arbitrary truncation. It should also reject vacuous predicates that are true
    96	  only because the branch weakens closure until it becomes trivial.
    97	- If Step 2 fails, that is not a mid-chain setback. It already settles most of
    98	  the chain's downstream ambition: the implication question is not theorem-ready
    99	  because the target object is not frozen.
   100	
   101	### Step 3 - Populate The Relation Matrix With The Carried Witnesses
   102	
   103	This step breaks the branch's own freeze discipline.
   104	
   105	- Step 7 froze the downstream witness to the single packet `F_SS(1/12)`.
   106	- Step 3 now wants to populate the matrix with `F_SS(1/12)`, `F_SL(1/16)`, and
   107	  `F_DT(delta, eta)`.
   108	
   109	That is witness-set drift. `F_SL(1/16)` and especially the hostile family
   110	`F_DT(delta, eta)` may still be relevant historically, but they are not the
   111	same thing as the single frozen witness carried into Step 8. Reintroducing them
   112	here quietly changes the scope of the branch.
   113	
   114	The matrix also mixes unlike statuses:
   115	
   116	- gate pass or fail on repaired Step-6 screens,
   117	- closure status on the Step-8 frozen ledger,
   118	- and family-level versus witness-level objects.
   119	
   120	Those do not sit in one clean table unless the chain first re-derives them in a
   121	single exact domain. It has not done that.
   122	
   123	The biggest overreach is using `F_SS(1/12)` as a "separation witness." Step 8
   124	showed that the current record does not yet freeze one finite exact closed
   125	subsystem on the same ledger. That is not automatically the same as proving
   126	that `F_SS(1/12)` falsifies every honest finite-closure predicate, and it is
   127	certainly not yet a theorem that gate pass does not imply closure in the
   128	underlying mathematical sense.
   129	
   130	Kill-condition problem:
   131	
   132	- The stated kill condition watches for packet-semantics drift, which is good.
   133	- But it misses the more immediate failure: the branch has already drifted from
   134	  the Step-7 single-witness freeze just by reopening `F_SL` and `F_DT`.
   135	
   136	### Step 4 - Prove The Strongest Honest Separation Or Minimal Repair
   137	
   138	This step offers the wrong menu of honest outcomes.
   139	
   140	- One honest outcome is not a separation theorem or a repaired implication.
   141	  It is simply: "the closure object is still unfrozen, so no implication claim
   142	  is theorem-ready."
   143	- The chain treats that possibility mostly as a failure mode on the way to
   144	  stronger packaging, but it may actually be the main result.
   145	
   146	The "minimal repair" branch is especially dangerous. Without a strict
   147	anti-tautology rule, it invites exactly the wrong move:
   148	
   149	- add a support-level closure hypothesis,
   150	- add existence of the finite closed subsystem as an assumption,
   151	- or add some bespoke exact companion rule that is just closure in disguise.
   152	
   153	That would make the implication true by smuggling the target into the premise.
   154	Calling that a repair would be misleading.
   155	
   156	The proposed example
   157	"joint repaired admissibility does not imply finite honest closure"
